<br>
No such mob exists though, so either there's an ac cap, or mobs have only atk values in the ranges between say 1 and 1200, and 5000+ with no mobs having atks that would be in the range where an ac of 1600 is significantly better than say 1300.  I find that hard to believe.<br>
<br>
Real parses (on the same mob) however have shown a clear presence of an cap cap.  It goes something like this (figures made up):<br>
<br>
 1000 ac, you mitigate 50% of the damage<br>
 1100 ac, you mitigate 55% of the damage<br>
 1200 ac, you mitigate 60% of the damage<br>
 1300 ac, you mitigate 60.5% of the damage<br>
 1400 ac, you mitigate 61% of the damage<br>
 1500 ac, you mitigate 61.5% of the damage<br>
<br>
In other words, before the ac cap, you see steady increases in your mitigation against a given mob.. then suddenly, it drops off.  You still get minor increases (or perhaps they are statistical errors), but it levels off so much it's hardly worth it.<br>
<br>
Fixing stuff so that ac actually has value again (and making sure that Warriors will be the king of ac) solves a ton of problems.  It will even reduce the power of Complete Heal a bit, as warriors will benefit more from ac than hp.<br>
<br>
However, it's clear Verant are taking the easy way out.  Capping CHeal to 7500 and giving plate classes PoP AA skills that give INSANE increases in hitpoints is a clear indication that Verant intend to use hitpoints as the new form of how long a tank will last (whereas before it was a combination of AC and HP).  AC has become meaningless -- you just max it once, like you max your Run3 skill, and then focus on hp.<br>
